An empty catch block doesn’t mean nothing went wrong. It means you’ll never know when it does.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Here’s a block of code most Java developers have written at least once:
try {
processPayment(order);
} catch (Exception e) {
e.printStackTrace();
}The application continues. No alert fires. No log entry gets written. A payment silently failed, and the system carried on as if nothing happened. Three days later, a customer emails support wondering why their order never shipped.
That empty catch block — or the e.printStackTrace() that functions as one — is one of the most expensive lines of code in any Java codebase. Not because it's complex. Because it's invisible.
Junior Developers treat exception handling as something the compiler forces on them. They wrap code in try-catch to make errors go away and move on.
Senior Developers treat every exception as a signal. They ask: what failed, why did it fail, who needs to know, and what should happen next? Then they write code that answers those questions clearly.
Here are the patterns that separate the two.
1️⃣ Never Swallow an Exception Silently
